label("$2$", (1,0), S);
label("$3$", (1,1), S);
label("$4$", (0,1), S);
[/asy]

There are 4 possible states in this graph, and each state is connected to 2 other states. The entropy rate is the average number of bits of information needed to specify the next state in the random walk, given the current state.

To calculate the entropy rate, we can consider all possible sequences of states in the random walk. There are $4^4 = 256$ such sequences. For each sequence, we can calculate the number of bits needed to specify the next state, given the current state. The average of these numbers is the entropy rate.

It turns out that the entropy rate is always equal to the Shannon entropy of the transition matrix of the random walk. The Shannon entropy of a transition matrix is the sum of the probabilities of all states, times the logarithm of the probabilities of those states.

In this case, the transition matrix is:

$$P = \begin{bmatrix}
0 & 1/2 & 1/4 & 0 \\\
1/2 & 0 & 1/4 & 0 \\\
1/4 & 1/4 & 0 & 1/2 \\\
0 & 0 & 1/2 & 0
\end{bmatrix}$$

The Shannon entropy of this matrix is $\log_2(3)$ bits. Therefore, the entropy rate of the random walk is also $\log_2(3)$ bits.

